# Testing Standards

## Backend (JUnit 5 + Testcontainers)

### Test Naming Convention
```java
@Test
void executeCommand_givenValidGmailInput_returnsSuccessResponse() { ... }
void login_givenInvalidCredentials_throws401() { ... }
```

### Unit Tests (Service Layer)
- Mock all dependencies with `@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)` + `@Mock`
- Test every public service method — at minimum: happy path + one error path
- No Spring context loading in unit tests — keep them fast (<100ms each)

### Integration Tests (Controller + Repository)
- Use `@SpringBootTest` + `@AutoConfigureMockMvc` for controller tests
- Use Testcontainers (`@Testcontainers` + `@Container`) for real PostgreSQL
- Never use H2 in-memory — behaviour differs from PostgreSQL (e.g. case sensitivity, JSON)
- Apply `@Sql` to seed test data per test class

### Coverage Requirements (enforced by JaCoCo in CI)
- Line coverage: ≥ 60% across all modules
- Branch coverage: ≥ 50%
- Excluded from coverage: `entity/`, `dto/`, `config/`, generated code

## Frontend (Vitest + React Testing Library)

### What to Test
- Custom hooks: test with `renderHook` from RTL
- Service functions: mock `apiClient` with `vi.mock`, test error handling
- Complex utility functions: pure unit tests
- Page components: test critical user flows (form submit, redirect, error state)

### What NOT to Test
- Style/CSS — visual regression testing is separate
- Third-party library internals
- Simple pass-through components

### RTL Principles
```jsx
// ✅ Query by accessible role (preferred)
screen.getByRole('button', { name: /execute/i })
screen.getByLabelText(/email/i)

// ✅ Query by test-id (fallback for non-semantic elements)
screen.getByTestId('command-result')

// ❌ Never query by class name or CSS selector
```

### Mock Pattern for API Calls
```javascript
import { vi } from 'vitest'
import * as authService from '../services/authService'

vi.mock('../services/authService')
authService.getCurrentUser.mockResolvedValue({ id: 1, email: 'test@example.com' })
```

## CI Enforcement
- `mvn verify` (backend) and `npm test` (frontend) both run on every PR
- PRs cannot be merged with failing tests
- Coverage reports uploaded as PR artifacts for review
